<h1 class="hero-h">How to Write Investor Updates with Claude <em style="color:#00C853;font-style:italic;">Save 4-6 hours per update without losing your voice.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">Monthly investor updates are one of the highest-leverage uses of AI for founders. Done well, the workflow saves 4-6 hours per month while producing better-structured updates than most founders write under time pressure. Here's the workflow.</p>
<div class="tldr"><div class="tldr-l">Short answer</div><p class="tldr-p">Build an Investor Update Project loaded with your past updates, KPI structure, and investor preferences. Dump in this month's metrics + raw context; get a structured draft in 15 minutes. Edit heavily so the voice stays yours. Saves 4-6 hours per update while improving consistency.</p></div>
</div></div>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">Setup (one-time, 60-90 min)</h2><ol class="ol"><li><strong>Create a Claude Project</strong> called "Investor Updates."</li><li><strong>Load the knowledge:</strong> last 6-12 monthly updates, your KPI dashboard structure, list of investors and any specific things each cares about (briefly), notes on what makes your updates work vs not.</li><li><strong>Write the system prompt</strong> covering identity (you, the founder), the structure you use, voice guidelines, and explicit forbidden patterns.</li><li><strong>Test with one past update</strong>, give Claude the raw inputs from that month, see if it produces output close to what you actually sent. Refine until it does.</li></ol></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">Sample system prompt</h2><p class="body">"You are drafting the monthly investor update for [Company] in [Founder]'s voice. Match the structure and voice of the example updates in your knowledge. Forbidden words: \"thrilled,\" \"crushing it,\" \"unstoppable,\" \"to the moon.\" Required sections: 1) TLDR (3 bullets), 2) Numbers (revenue, ARR, key metrics vs plan), 3) Wins, 4) Concerns and what we're doing about them, 5) Asks of investors. Always include at least one Concern, investors trust founders who acknowledge difficulty. Be specific. Avoid corporate phrasing."</p></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">Monthly workflow (15-30 min)</h2><ol class="ol"><li>Open the Investor Update Project.</li><li>Paste this month's raw inputs: KPI numbers, 3-5 wins (in bullet form), 2-3 concerns, any asks, anything notable.</li><li>Ask: "Draft this month's investor update based on what I've pasted. Match my voice."</li><li>Review the draft. Edit aggressively, change phrasing, add color, sharpen specifics.</li><li>Send.</li></ol></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">What to keep human</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>The Concerns section.</strong> Investors trust honest founders. Your authentic phrasing about what's hard matters more here than anywhere else.</li><li><strong>Anything sensitive.</strong> Co-founder issues, exec changes, customer churns. Draft these yourself.</li><li><strong>The Ask.</strong> Specific asks need your judgment about which investor can help with what.</li><li><strong>The numbers themselves.</strong> Pull from your accounting/dashboard, not from AI. AI describes; humans report.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">Common founder mistakes</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>Skipping the example load.</strong> Without past updates as examples, Claude produces generic VC-speak. Always load examples.</li><li><strong>Sending without editing.</strong> Investors smell AI-written updates. Edit until the voice is yours.</li><li><strong>Hiding bad news.</strong> AI will produce technically-true-but-rosy phrasing if asked. Don't ask for that.</li><li><strong>Too long.</strong> Update should be under 600 words. AI tends to be verbose. Cut.</li><li><strong>Forgetting to update the Project knowledge.</strong> Each month, add this month's update to the knowledge so future drafts get sharper.</li></ul></div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">FAQ</h2>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">Will investors notice it's AI-assisted?</h3><p class="faq-qa">If you don't edit, yes. If you do edit so the voice is yours, no.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">Should I tell investors I use AI for updates?</h3><p class="faq-qa">Don't volunteer it; don't lie if asked. Most investors understand and won't care.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">How long should an investor update be?</h3><p class="faq-qa">400-600 words for monthly; 800-1200 for quarterly. AI will tend longer. Cut.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">What if a metric is bad?</h3><p class="faq-qa">Include it. Frame the concern. Investors trust founders who acknowledge difficulty more than founders who hide it.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">Should the update be different for different investors?</h3><p class="faq-qa">Same core update for everyone; optional 1-paragraph personalized note for lead investors. Keep the personal touch.</p></div>
</div></section>

